// Semantic direction:
// http_request pairs a method, target, version, headers, and optional body.
// request_target is the path and query string portion of the URL.
// content_length is the byte count of the body; transfer_encoding chunked means the body arrives in chunks.
// parse_chunked_body reads hex chunk_size, then chunk_data, repeating until a zero-size chunk terminates.
// etag_header is a cache validator; if_none_match sends the stored etag to enable conditional GETs.
// http1_parser reads bytes from a TCP stream and emits structured request or response objects.
// http1_writer serializes a request or response into bytes for transmission.
// http2 multiplexes multiple logical h2_streams over one TCP connection.
// h2_preface is the fixed magic bytes a client sends to start an HTTP/2 connection.
// h2_frame is the basic unit of HTTP/2 communication: a fixed header plus type-specific payload.
// frame_settings negotiates parameters (header table size, initial window, concurrent_streams limit).
// frame_window_update increases flow_control_h2 credit so the sender can transmit more bytes.
// hpack compresses HTTP/2 headers using a static table, a dynamic hpack_table, and Huffman coding.
// hpack_encode reduces headers to a few bytes when the same name-value pair has been sent before.
// stream_dependency and stream_weight implement HTTP/2 priority for scheduling frames.
// server_push lets the server send push_promise frames to proactively deliver resources the client will need.
// http_connection_pool reuses idle connections to the same host; pool_per_host limits concurrency.
// connection_reuse sends multiple HTTP/1.1 requests on one TCP connection using keep_alive_hdr.
// idle_timeout_http closes connections that have been inactive for too long.

// Primitive flow:
// HTTP/1.1 server: tcp_accept -> http1_parser reads bytes
//   -> parse_request_line + parse_headers_h1 + body (chunked or fixed length)
//   -> handler(request) -> http_response -> http1_writer -> tcp_write
// HTTP/2 client: tcp_connect + TLS ALPN "h2" -> send h2_preface
//   -> frame_settings exchange -> open h2_stream(stream_id=1)
//   -> hpack_encode(headers) -> frame_headers -> frame_data (body)
//   -> receive frame_headers + frame_data -> hpack_decode -> http_response
// Flow control: initial_window=65535 -> send data -> window decreases
//   -> receive frame_window_update -> window restored -> send more

// This defines HTTP/1.1 parsing and writing, chunked encoding, HTTP/2 framing,
// HPACK header compression, stream multiplexing, and connection pooling.
